messages.text:
The horned rattlesnake ‚Äì one of the rattlesnakes found in the southern deserts of North America-makes a throw in 100 milliseconds. However, kangaroo jumpers, which rattlesnakes hunt, react to danger even faster ‚Äì they need only 70 milliseconds to jump away from the snake, and some jumpers can do it even in 38 milliseconds.¬†

For a long time, zoologists could not understand how rodents get away from the lightning-fast throw of rattlesnakes, and only now researchers from the University of California, riverside, using a very high-speed camera, were able to see that jumpers are actually even more lightning-fast than snakes. This protection is very effective ‚Äì only one of the five jumpers gets the snake for lunch.

text:
The helmet-nosed Basilisk is an arboreal lizard that lives in tropical rainforests. A distinctive feature of the Basilisk is the ability to run on water, keeping its body on the surface with rapidly alternating blows of its hind legs. The Basilisk can run on water up to 400 meters at a speed of 12 km/h.
Because of its ability to run on water, Costa Ricans refer to the helmet-nosed Basilisk as the "lizard of Jesus Christ".

messages.text:
This amazing inhabitant of the rainforest ‚Äì velvet worm hunts by shooting its prey with slime-a special quickly drying sticky substance. The body of this segmented worm is covered with many small hairs and resembles velvet.¬†
The mucus mass is about 11% of the total weight and consists mainly of water and some proteins.
In order to detect the victim, the velvet worm detects the smallest changes in the movement of air flows by special protrusions on the skin, which are equipped with chemical sensors. When the victim comes into his field of vision, he shoots a jet of mucus up to 30 cm from the papillae at the head of the bed. After the slime reaches the victim, it quickly dries and immobilizes it. The worm injects the victim with its saliva and digestive enzymes, then sucks out the resulting "broth".

text:
Orchid mantises are quite aggressive and bold insects. They can attack large insects and even small lizards. Adults can fly. Mantises hunt on flowers, freezing and pretending to be part of the flower. When an insect approaches at close range, the mantis quickly grabs it with its strong paws. Orchid mantises live in the rainforests of India and Indonesia.
Because of its attractive appearance, the Orchid mantis is in demand among fans of exotic insects.

text:
Nature has given many creatures an unusual appearance that allows them to scare off enemies and survive among predators. The caterpillar of the great harpy has an impressive Arsenal for intimidating enemies.¬†
While the caterpillar is at rest, it is almost impossible to notice it among the greenery. At the moment of danger, the caterpillar of a large harpy raises its front part of the body, showing the enemy its "face"and front legs in black and white. After it lifts up the back of the body and shows the tail processes, similar to the sting. If the enemy does not give up, the caterpillar uses a real weapon-the iron, which is located in the front of the chest. The gland produces a caustic substance containing about 40% formic acid. The caterpillar can spray acid for a long distance. Therefore, when you see a terrible harpy, you need to protect your eyes.

messages.text: Amazing movements of the Chaka phyllomedusa.¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†¬†They live in the crown of tall trees and perfectly climb on thin twigs and leaves. Unlike other tree frogs, phyllomedusa do not have suckers on their toes, but they are able to grasp tenaciously with their long, thin fingers. It is impossible to detach a phyllomedusa from a branch without injuring its paw. Her movements are slow, smooth, and careful. She is able to jump, but rarely does so. Phyllomedusa walks like a toad on flat ground, and in water it is very helpless, since its swimming webs are poorly developed or completely absent.

messages.text:
Metamorphosis (complete transformation) occurs at the entire stage of the pupal life cycle.
From a voracious caterpillar that only cared about food, a butterfly will produce offspring. But the pupa itself is vulnerable, since it does not have the ability to crawl away from danger, or fly away. That is why nature has taken care of masking the pupae, some species can not be distinguished from twigs or leaves, and many subspecies weave cocoons of many kilometers of silk thread, in which the caterpillars turn into pupae. The life cycle of the pupa depends on the type of butterfly, for some it lasts only a few days, and sometimes up to three years.

messages.text:
Fight Komodo dragons, Rinca island, Indonesia

The Komodo lizard is the largest extant lizard and the heaviest modern representative of scaly lizards: individual representatives of this species can grow more than 3 meters in length and weigh more than 130 kilograms. Biologists estimate that there are fewer than 5,000 Komodo lizards in nature.

There is something predatory and "reptilian" about this bird. Like a little dinosaur in feathers. This bird spends most of its time on the ground and hunts snakes, lizards, insects, rodents, and small birds.
It is fast enough to kill even small vipers, which it grabs by the tail with its beak and hits its head on the ground like a whip. It swallows its prey whole.
Ground cuckoos are unimportant fliers, and prefer to run on the ground, mainly along roads. They can reach speeds of up to 30 kilometers per hour: enough to catch a fast-moving rattlesnake. After catching up with the snake, the cuckoo grabs its tail, swings it like a whip, and hits its head on the ground. The bird swallows all its prey whole.

text:
The glow itself, its duration, and rhythm vary between species (so as not to confuse them). Females of most species do not signal in flight: on their own initiative, or in response to a signal from a male.
 In some species, females are able to mimic the signals of females of other species, luring other males to eat.

messages.text:
Many people think that their tongue is "responsible" for the snake's hiss, but this is not so!
 Snakes don't have vocal cords, so they extract a specific sound we know by directing air through a small opening in the larynx. When the snake releases air "normally", we do not hear any suspicious sounds. And when the air is released "hard", it moves and begins to vibrate a special cartilage located in the glottis.

Despite a vegetarian diet consisting of 99% bamboo, the animal can eat meat. Pandas have been known to hunt small rodents.
 In summer, pandas can move up to 4,000 meters to escape the heat. In winter, they do not hibernate and do not set up a den.

text:
Mimosa modesty destroys the stereotypes of plants as immobile creatures, indifferent to the events of the outside world. To protect itself from pests, Mimosa folds leaves in response to touch. The reaction is surprisingly fast.¬†
 The mechanism of movement is based on the rapid loss of water by cells located at the base of each leaf of a complex leaf. It is the intracellular water pressure (turgor) that allows all plants to maintain their shape. Interestingly, in response to touch, there are currents of ions through the membrane, as we have in the nervous system, so you can start the same reaction with an electric pulse.

We continue the "bearish" weekend. 
A newborn baby Koala reaches a length of no more than 2 centimeters, it has no hair and is completely blind. After birth, the cub is taken to the mother's bag, where it has protection and nutrition for another 6 months.
When the cub leaves the bag, it still stays with the mother for 6 months or more, moving with her, sitting on her back, and can eat both milk and eucalyptus leaves. 
Now a "small" correction: a Koala is not a bear!

messages.text:
The Panda ant (Euspinolia militaris) is an unusual insect that belongs to the German wasp family. Their body is covered with fine hairs, for which they received their second name "velvet ants", in fact, having nothing to do with them.

text:
The main dangerous enemy of the zebra is the african lion, which loves the meat of this animal and considers it a delicacy. Most often, a predator waits for its prey on the way to a watering hole or looks for young individuals who have strayed from the herd.
During danger, a relative of a horse can reach speeds of up to 70 km / h, which does not always allow predators to eat their delicious meat. Zebra can run very deftly zigzags, confusing even very experienced hunters.
The zebra defends itself with powerful hooves that hit the enemy with all the strength, sometimes such a blow can be fatal.

messages.text:
The Kermode or Kermode bear is a subspecies of the American black bear (baribal) that lives exclusively in the forests of the west coast of Canada.
Approximately 10 % of the Kermode bear population has a white or cream coat color.
¬†These bears are not albinos. They are also not related to polar bears. The Kermode bear was named after Francis Kermode, who first described it. The local Indian tribes bear a different name - spirit bear.

This coat color serves as a kind of camouflage for Kermode bears when fishing for salmon on the river, which helps them get enough of more fish than their relatives with dark hair.

messages.text: The lyrebird's song is its most distinctive characteristic. Lyrebirds sing throughout the year, most of them sing during the breeding season, which runs from June to August. During this time, they can sing for up to four hours a day-almost half the daylight hours. A lyrebird song consists of seven elements of its own songs and any number of other songs and sounds that it can successfully imitate.

Black panthers differ from other animals in their bravery, as they are not afraid of people, and can easily approach their homes. They are predators and hunt at night. Black panthers are good at climbing trees and are famous for their deadly high jumps.

text.text: How does the chicken breathe inside the egg?

text:
‚†Ä
For metabolism and development, the embryo in the egg, like an adult bird (or reptile), needs to inhale oxygen and remove the product of metabolism ‚Äî carbon dioxide.
‚†Ä
How does a chicken breathe? It's all about the air bag between the two membranes under the shell ‚Äî the outer and inner. The bag is formed when the newly laid egg cools, the white and yolk decrease in size and a cavity appears under the shell. Through the pores in the shell, air is sucked in from the outside. There are about 7000 pores and it is through them that gas exchange occurs between the bag inside the egg and the atmosphere. Warm carbon dioxide escapes, cold air with oxygen is sucked in.

messages.text:
Ant circles (ant rotation, death spiral, death carousel) ‚Äî a natural phenomenon that consists in the fact that one or a small group of ants begins to run around in a closed circle for no apparent reason, gradually involving more and more other ants in its endless cycle.

For the first time, this phenomenon was thoroughly described in 1944 by the American zoophysiologist Theodore Schnereila, who gave it the name death mill, because ants continue their run until they fall dead and the carousel of death continues its rotation until its participants are completely exhausted, leaving behind hordes of dead ants.

messages.text:
The weasel is the smallest predator among mammals.
During the day, the weasel eats 10-15 rodents (40% of its own weight) and often kills more. The animal leaves extra prey in reserve. In the storerooms of the burrow there can be from 30 to 100 mice. This saves the weasel in the days of unsuccessful hunting. Without food, the animal can die within 4 hours.

messages.text:
Pudu belongs to the genus of mammals of the deer family. These are the smallest deer in the world. They live in Chile. Their body length is from 80 to 93 cm, height at the withers is 30-40 cm, weight from 7 to 10 kg. Pudu feed on shoots, leaves, and bark. With such a diet, they may not drink for a long time.
Fleeing from a predator, pudu is able to run into a tilted tree. The animals are on the verge of extinction, because of their miniature size, the pudu become easy prey for predators and poachers.

messages.text:
The clouded leopard occupies an intermediate position between small and large cats. Contrary to its name, this predator is not directly related to the real leopards and is considered a fairly ancient species, as well as a possible ancestor of the current large cats.
Because of the precious skin, the clouded leopard was hunted a lot in the past. Today it is threatened by poaching, but the greatest threat to its conservation is the progressive deforestation of the rainforests that are its home. Of the four subspecies, the Taiwanese clouded leopard (Neofelis nebulosa brachyurus) is already extinct. The entire species is classified as endangered.

It lives in the north-eastern part of South America, its range includes the following countries: Guyana, Suriname and French Guiana, as well as north-eastern Brazil to the north of the Amazon.
These primates are active during the day. Most of the time they spend in the trees, moving on all fours or jumping. They live in groups of 2 to 6 individuals, in exceptional cases up to 15 animals. These groups consist of a dominant female, other subordinate females, one or more males, and a common younger generation.
The red-handed tamarin is an omnivore. It feeds on fruits, insects, nectar, and tree sap.

The appearance of this bear is so peculiar that it has received the nickname "sloth bear".
The sloth bear is very different in appearance and lifestyle from real bears, and it is separated into a separate genus.
The sloth bear, like the anteater, has evolved to feed mainly on colonial insects (ants and termites), which is atypical for other bears, in whose diet insects play a minor role.

messages.text:
The red river hogs are considered the most variegated colored hogs.¬†
The red river hogs live in West and Central Africa, their range extends from Senegal to the Democratic Republic of the Congo. They are found both in forests and in savannas and swampy areas, avoiding only too arid landscapes.
The red river hogs are active at night, and they spend the day in burrows, usually hidden in dense vegetation. This species lives in family groups of 2 to 15 individuals, led by a mature male.
The red river hogs are omnivores, feeding on roots, tubers, and fruits, as well as insects, small invertebrates, and carrion.

messages.text:
Pangolins are the only mammals with scales. ü¶°¬†
The pangolin is similar in appearance to an anteater. The main distinguishing feature is the presence of armor made of solid plates. It covers almost the entire body of the pangolin except for the belly, nose and inner side of the paws. The hard protective plates on its back make it look like an armadillo.

messages.text: The ability of furry mammals to quickly get rid of water is a necessary survival technique used by mice, dogs, and large predators such as bears to help them prevent the development of hypothermia. Wet wool loses its ability to insulate when warm air is trapped near the skin. Shaking is an effective way to get rid of the water and it consumes less energy than waiting for the sun to evaporate all the water in their fur.

messages.text:
The Guinea turaco is a tropical bird in the family Turaceae. It is distributed in the lowland and floodplain forests of West Africa from Senegal east to the Democratic Republic of the Congo, south to northern Angola.
The diet consists mainly of fruits of tropical plants-dates, wild figs, musanga, ficus, makaranga, rauwolfia, cissus, nightshade. In addition, it eats flowers and buds.

African antelope gerenuk.
In dry areas, gerenuki can go without water for a very long time. They feed exclusively on leaves and, like the unrelated giraffes, have evolved long necks and limbs for this purpose.
In order to reach the tall branches, the Gerenuk stands on its hind legs, leaning its front legs against the trunk of a tree.

messages.text: For wolves, a typical family lifestyle: they live in packs of up to 40 individuals ‚Äî family groups consisting of a pair of leaders-an alpha male and an alpha female, their relatives, as well as newcomers. Within the pack, there is a strictly defined hierarchy, at the top of which is the dominant pair, then adult family members, lone wolves, and finally the puppies of the last litter. As you can see on the record, a strict hierarchy does not prevent gray predators from having fun.

messages.text:
Gibbon marks his territory with vocals.

The power of sound in the songs of gibbons is very different and depends, as you can see, on the distance from the singing other monkeys are. The animal makes sounds of such power that it is sufficient for its singing to be heard and understood by its neighbors-relatives. Apparently, this singing is like notifying the neighbors that the tree or the area where the singer is located is occupied.

messages.text:
A sniper.
The peregrine falcon is the fastest bird, capable of developing the highest speed among all living creatures on the planet. Among falcons, the peregrine falcon can only share the glory with its relative the gyrfalcon. The peregrine falcon's main weapon is its relatively long legs with strong and clawed toes. The impact of the clawed paws at high speed cuts through the victim's body like a cutter.
The flight of the peregrine falcon is easy with frequent flaps of its wings, but in horizontal flight the peregrine falcon develops a speed of no more than 100-110 km / h. The peregrine falcon is not such a successful predator. But these falcons have a secret weapon - a swift dive. Here the peregrine falcon has no equal in the world of animals, because in the fall of his body cuts the air at a speed of 240-300 km / h! This is the highest speed recorded among all living things in general.

messages.text:
Kangaroos love to scratch! They do this often ‚Äî this is their daily ritual.

Kangaroos live in savannas, where you can not hide from dust and dry grass, which can stick to the coat and get tangled in it. And regular scratching is a great way to remove all the excess from the coat. Including unpleasant ticks that feed on the blood of kangaroos.

messages.text:
A baby king penguin.

A fluffy fur coat allows the chicks to survive the first year of life, when they still barely retain heat in their body without a layer of fat under the skin. Because of this, they do not dive for fish on their own, they are carefully fed by their parents, so much so that by the end of the first year, the chick may be heavier than the mother!!

messages.text:
She can't be a butterfly anymore.

The Venus flycatcher catches its victims (insects, arachnids) with a specialized fishing device formed from the edge parts of the leaves. The closing of the trap is initiated by thin trigger (sensitive) hairs on the surface of the leaves. To close the trap device, it is necessary to exert a mechanical effect on at least two hairs on the sheet with an interval of no more than 20 seconds. This selectivity provides protection against accidental slamming in response to falling objects that have no nutritional value (raindrops, debris, etc.). Moreover, digestion begins after at least five times the stimulation of sensitive hairs.

messages.text:
Muscular Kangaroo Roger
Roger is known online for his unusually large muscles. He lived in an animal shelter in Alice Springs. During his life in the shelter, the kangaroo grew by more than 2 m and weighed 89 kg. The popularity of Roger was brought in 2015 by a video in which he squeezed metal buckets with his strength.
Shelter manager Chris Barnes said there was nothing unusual about his strength, but he was different from other kangaroos. Roger died in 2018 at the age of 12.

messages.text:
Do you know why the goats of Morocco graze on trees?

Morocco is the only country where goats graze not on the ground, but on trees. This is due to an acute shortage of grass. At the same time, goats in Morocco do not belong to any special species. The ability to maintain balance is inherent, it turns out, in all goats. Goats climb the argan trees growing here, where they eat foliage and fruits.¬†

The task of shepherds, as a rule, is not only to drive goats from tree to tree and control the herd, but also to collect bones from the fruits of argonia, which the goats spit out. They produce valuable argan oil used in cosmetology and cooking.

Is it a bird?¬†Is it a plane?¬†No, it's a Curculion weevil!¬†Unfolding its hardy elytra and releasing the flaps of its hind wings, the insect takes off like a shape-shifting transformer.¬†Often the beetle lifts the second pair of legs together with the initial hole, then lifts all the limbs and takes off.

A resident of the Stavropol Territory (Russia) found a live "rat king" in a watermelon field. Previously, rat pups with tangled tails were found only dead, which cast doubt on this phenomenon.

text: Babies.

(Cebuella pygmaea) is a marmoset species, a very small New World monkey found in the northwestern Amazon Rainforest in Brazil, Colombia, Ecuador, and Peru. It was formerly regarded as conspecific with the similar eastern pygmy marmoset, which has whitish underparts. Although the western pygmy marmoset occurs further west than the eastern pygmy marmoset, the primary separators of their ranges are the Amazon River (Solim√µes River) and Maranon River, with the western occurring to the north of them and the eastern to the south.

messages.text:
Important news - the Japanese "queen of macaques" is now caught in a complicated love triangle  which threatens her rule.
A macaque named Yakei rules a clan of 677 Japanese macaques (this pack is over 70 years old), known to Internet users for their love of hot springs.¬†
Recently, she carried out an armed revolution, beat and overthrew the alpha male of the pack, becoming the first female leader in the history of her clan, which amazed Japanese zoologists (matriarchs among this primate species are very rare).
But now the mating season is coming ‚Äî now two males are fighting for her heart at once: Takei (18 years old), who the young queen really likes, but he cruelly rejected her last mating season, and Luffy, who courted her for a long time and then began abusing and beating the ruler and now she is afraid of him (if he beats her a couple more times, he will manipulate and control the pack through her) .
And you say everything is difficult in your personal life!

But now the mating season is coming ‚Äî now two males are fighting for her heart at once: Takei (18 years old), who the young queen really likes, but he cruelly rejected her last mating season, and Luffy, who courted her for a long time and then began abusing and beating the ruler and now she is afraid of him (if he beats her a couple more times, he will manipulate and control the pack through her) .
And you say everything is difficult in your personal life!

messages.text:
This is the arboreal kangaroo Dendrolagus. He, like an ordinary kangaroo, has a long tail and a bag for carrying cubs, but he is small and jumps not on the grass, but from branch to branch.

Curved claws help him to stay firmly on trees, and a powerful tail balances the body in nimble jumps.
¬†On
the ground, this animal moves slowly and clumsily: the tail is very heavy, and the hind legs are too short. Our kangaroo rarely descends down, but if necessary, it can easily jump from a ten-meter height.

He has almost no enemies on the trees, and there is plenty of plant food!

messages.text:
The California crested quail Callipepla californica inhabit the west coast of North America. In addition, the species has been introduced to Hawaii, New Zealand, Chile and Argentina.

It is a sedentary bird that lives in groups of 10 to 40 individuals and prefers to find food on the ground, but quails spend the night in trees.

The California crested quail feeds mainly on the seeds of herbaceous plants. Adult birds also feed to a small extent on small arthropods.

These birds are very popular as decorative, they get along very well in aviaries together with other bird species. However, it is not recommended to keep them together with other chicken.

And the last: this is the national bird of the state of California!

In 2014, a young elephant fought off fourteen lionesses. The heroic battle was filmed, and the elephant was nicknamed Hercules.

The incident occurred in Zambia, in the South Luangwa National Park. Hungry lionesses surrounded a stray young elephant from the herd and launched an attack.¬†

Tourists were watching the scene. They were sure that the young animal would die now. However, the elephant turned out to be resourceful: choosing the right moment, he ran into the water right with one of the lionesses on his back. When the lionesses began to chase him in the water, he turned around and chased them himself.

This event surprised not only tourists, but also specialists. Joyce Poole,  an expert at National Geographic, said that he knows only one such case, but he is inferior to this incident.

Poole once watched a lioness attack a baby elephant, but his parents were nearby, and they chased the predator away. The situation when one young animal can cope with the attack of more than a dozen lions is unique...

text:
Matchmaking of an albatross.

The royal albatross

has the largest wingspan of all flying birds (280-320 cm) and weighs up to 8 kg.

The royal albatross reaches sexual maturity by the age of 6-10. Lays one white egg. Egg incubation lasts 80 days. Feeding of the chick lasts 34-38 days. The mating period is November - December. It breeds on the islands of Chatham, Campbell and Auckland in the South Pacific Ocean, as well as in the south of New Zealand.

The average life expectancy of a royal albatross is 58 years. Low fertility and long development are compensated by long life expectancy and low mortality of adult birds. According to statistics, only three out of a hundred albatrosses die every year

text: The Takahe (wingless sultan)

is a flightless rare bird found in the mountains of the South Island of New Zealand.

It looks very similar to an ordinary sultanka, but much larger (the size of a domestic goose). The wings are developed normally, but the muscles of the keel and sternum are underdeveloped, the bird does not fly.

Takahe's plumage is beautiful and the appearance of a rare bird is remembered immediately. The color of the feathers located on the head and throat is dominated by black tones, the large beak is painted red, the chest and neck shimmer with a variety of colors: from blue to purple.

At one time it was considered completely extinct, now it has the status of a species in danger of extinction in the International Red Book.
The New Zealand Government declared Takahe habitats a 500 square km nature reserve, where people's access was strictly limited. The modern nature reserve at Lake Te Anau is part of the Fiordland National Park, which covers an area of 160,000 hectares

messages.text:
The elephant shrew (or elephant jumper) was so named for its elongated movable nose, resembling a miniature trunk. Despite the name, this animal has nothing to do with shrews and for the most part runs, although it can also jump quite well. Surprisingly, elephant shrews are similar to elephants not only in appearance - they are indeed relatives.

On the tail, on the soles and on the chest of the jumpers there are sebaceous glands that secrete an odorous substance with which they mark the grass and paths on their territory. The animals carefully take care of their thick fur and "comb" it with their hind paw several times a day, standing on the three remaining ones.

The animals are very timid and at the slightest noise or incomprehensible movement they break off and run away. Fleeing from persecution, they move in long jumps, and if necessary, they can jump in length or jump up 40 cm or higher

text: Enea's mouse (dwarf mouse-like possum)

belongs to marsupials, although they do not have a brood pouch. And they do not live in Australia, but in South America between the Amazon and the Orinoco. Here is such a mysterious little animal!

The color of the upper side of the body is yellowish-gray, the lower side is lighter. The total length is up to 30 cm, of which the naked prehensile tail accounts for about 18 cm.

This opossum leads a nocturnal arboreal lifestyle, it is omnivorous, but prefers fruits and insects.

There are up to 15 cubs in the litter. First they hang on the nipples, then they "ride" on the female's back

text: Sugar Flying Marsupial (sugar flying possum)

is a small animal resembling a squirrel. Body length 15-21 cm and the same tail, weight 95-170 g.

A feature of the flying marsupials is the membrane, which starts from the fifth toes of the front paws and ends on the first toes of the hind paws. When jumping, the animals stretch their paws to the sides, pulling the membrane, which allows them to "glide" through the air for considerable distances (up to 50 m or more). The flight course is regulated by the movement of the paws and tail.

Twisting the tail into a spring, possums can carry small objects - for example, twigs for a nest. Since they are nocturnal animals, their large and bulging eyes are adapted for night vision.

Flying possums live in Australia, New Guinea and Tasmania

text: The bicolor porcupine

is found in Bolivia, Peru, Ecuador and Colombia.

It leads a nocturnal, arboreal, secretive lifestyle, but adult couples can live together in tree hollows. Moves slowly, while quickly climbing a tree. It feeds on leaves, fruits, seeds and bark of plants.

It moves slowly and can remain stationary for a long time. The prehensile tail and adapted legs allow it to move easily between branches. Prefers to settle in the hollows of trees higher from the ground.

This is a relatively small porcupine: body length 40-55 cm, weight 3-5 kg. The nose and lips are noticeable, tuberous, the eyes are small, black. The ears are small, inconspicuous, hidden among the fur.

The most amazing thing about it is, of course, the coloring! It was as if a maniac was running through the jungle with a spray can and generously sprayed it...

text:
night monkeys (durukuls) are the only monkeys of the New World active at night.

They are common in Central and South America, live in family groups and feed mainly on fruits.

Nocturnal monkeys are relatively small primates with a body length of 25-35 cm and a tail of 30 to 40 cm . The weight varies from 0.7 to 1.2 kg, long and fluffy, its tip is often black. Unlike several other New World monkeys, it cannot be used for grabbing.

During rest periods, nocturnal monkeys retire into hollows or dense thickets. About 15 minutes after sunset, they get out of their sleeping places and are active until midnight, after which they rest again for an hour and a half to two hours before they start looking for food again. Before sunrise, they retire again to their resting places.

In this video, mom, dad and baby night monkeys sleep in a hollow tree during the day to hide from potential predators

text: Madagascar Comet (moon moth)

is a beautiful moth of the peacock‚Äìeyed family. This is one of the largest butterflies in the world. Its wingspan reaches 140-160 mm. It is also called Madagascar Saturnia.

The moon moth is even depicted on a banknote of 5000 Malagasy francs (ariari, the monetary unit of the state of Madagascar) of the 1995 model.

And about the sad. The oral organs of both females and males are reduced, the butterflies do not feed on anything and live off the nutrients accumulated in the caterpillar stage - thus these beautiful butterflies live for only 4-5 days.

During this time, they should have time to find a mate and leave offspring

text: At the bottom of the Indian Ocean there is an unusual

- a sea slug that looks like a little rabbit!

This slug was first discovered in the waters off the Japanese coast in 1938, then it was forgotten about - and only with the advent of the Internet, photos and videos of this mollusk began to spread on the network. The Japanese were very interested in this wonderful sea slug, so similar to a fluffy rabbit.

The body of the slug is covered with small needle-like structures called spicules - it seems that it is covered with fur. Perhaps they play the role of sensitive sensors.

On the head of the slug there are two antennae, similar to the long ears of a rabbit - in fact, these are the sensory organs of a mollusk, whose task is to detect chemicals in the water, so that the slug can navigate and find food. There is a flower-shaped tail at the back, which is actually gills. The length of this "rabbit" is only 2.5 cm

text: The Malayan woolwing

lives in Thailand, the Malay Peninsula and various islands of the Indonesian archipelago, including Sumatra, Java and Borneo.

Prefers, first of all, moist jungles in hilly areas, but is also found on coconut and banana plantations.

This kind of animal lives in trees and never voluntarily descends to the ground. These are solitary animals, occasionally you can meet several individuals on the same tree.

They use a gliding flight to move from one tree to another without touching the ground. More often they fly at a distance of up to 50-70 m, the record flight range was 136 m. The animals are active at night, spending the day in their shelter.

They are herbivores. They feed on flowers, leaves, buds and fruits.

The body length of the Malay woolwing is 30-40 cm, the tail is 15-20 cm. The span of the limbs is 70-120 cm, and the weight is 1-1.75 kg

text:
horseshoe crabs are one of the most ancient arthropods on Earth that have survived to the present day. All their relatives (scorpions, ticks, haymakers) settled on land more than 400 million years ago, and only horseshoe crabs remained faithful to the marine environment.¬†

They are so ancient that using the example of these arthropods, they study the behavior of trilobites, which completely died out a quarter of a billion years ago: how they shed, changing the old skin, or escaped from their pursuers.

Horseshoe crabs breathe through their gills, but they can also move on land, since the special structure of the gills allows them to absorb oxygen from the air while the gills retain moisture.
The horseshoe crab's blood is not red, but blue because of the high content of copper in it.

text: Kakomycli

is a small animal resembling a cross between a marten and a cat. It has excellent climbing skills and destroys a lot of rodents, because it was often tamed before. Now they are less common as pets, but in North America they are sometimes kept ‚Äì they are kind and affectionate pets, unless not everyone can get used to their voice.

In fact, kakomitsli belongs to the raccoon family. This animal is 30-45 cm long and plus another 30-50 cm falls on its tail, but its entire length does not exceed 1300 g.

Some people are not fastidious in their diet and eat everything they find on their site. These are insects, small or large rodents - even rabbits, squirrels, and birds. In addition to animal food, kakomitsli also willingly eats persimmons, mistletoe, other fruits and plants.

These interesting animals live in the southern and southwestern regions of the United States at altitudes up to 2900 m above sea level, as well as in Mexico and Central America

text: Speckled Marsupial marten (quoll)

is the size of a small cat - body length 45 cm, tail - up to 30 cm, weight - up to 1.5 kg.

The Latin name of the quolla translates as: "A ferret-like animal with a fluffy tail." Quoll has nothing to do with real European martens, but the first settlers of Australia were almost entirely convicts, among whom for some reason there were no biologists...

For this reason, we now have an Australian magpie, which is not a magpie at all - and many similar other curiosities.

The lifestyle of the Quoll is solitary and nocturnal. They usually hunt on the ground, but they are good at climbing trees. The main food of the quoll is insect pests.

After the colonization of Australia, they began to hunt poultry, rabbits, rats and mice and were exterminated by farmers for ruining poultry houses - and now the quoll is found only in Tasmania.¬†

The main food competitor of the quoll is the Tasmanian devil, as well as human-introduced foxes, feral cats and dogs

text: The tannid wasps (flower wasps)

are a family of large solitary wasps whose larvae parasitize the larvae of beetles, especially scarabs.

Females, of course, are searching for beetle larvae. Males feed on nectar and are secondary pollinators.

In this video you can watch how orchids deceive male wasps by pretending to be their females! The male rushes to the flower, and... All covered with pollen! Then he flies to another deceptive orchid, and... Everything repeats again.

This is how this wasp Casanova transfers pollen from orchid to orchid... What a deception! Interestingly, from a human point of view, the similarity between a flower and a wasp is small - but wasps see in a different spectrum and everything is different for them!

text:
is a species of saber-horned antelope found in Eastern and Southern Africa.

The chamois is the personification of endurance and unpretentiousness, so it is depicted on the coat of arms of Namibia. From time immemorial, the aborigines have used Oryx skins for clothing, and horns as spearheads.

Long and sharp horns are the first thing that catches the eye when describing these ungulates: they can reach a length of up to one and a half meters!

Oryx itself is not small, at the withers it reaches 1 m 20 cm. A characteristic feature of this species of oryx is a black-and-white muzzle, similar to a mask.

Chamois usually live in arid regions (deserts and semi-deserts), but they are also found in savannas. Their range stretches from Ethiopia and Somalia to Namibia and South Africa.

Oryx prefer to eat herbs, but they are also able to dig up roots, and also eat wild fruits. Although they sometimes drink water, they can do without reservoirs, as they cover their water supply from food.

text:
The word "jellyfish" usually conjures up an image of a gentle creature floating in the water column - disc-shaped, like aurelia, or mushroom-shaped with long tentacled threads, like cyanea.

But there are jellyfish that can, but "don't like" to swim. They turn upside down and float to the bottom, cling to it with a dome and continue to actively "float", pumping water on themselves.

For example, the colorful Mediterranean jellyfish

does this. In English, these jellyfish are called: "upside-down jellyfish" ("inverted jellyfish").

They live on mudflats, shallow lagoons and in mangroves, and their legs are often mistaken for the legs of anemones. Cassiopea andromeda is carnivorous and eats small marine animals, which it kills with stinging cells.

The jellyfish throws these cells up in a cloud, so it's better not to swim near it - you can get burned!

text: The African ferret (zorilla)

is the most smelly animal after the skunk! In this video, a couple of gorillas are hunting a snake.

When a dog or other enemy appears, the zorilla ruffles its fur, raises its tail, and then uses the fragrant musky secret of its anal glands. The zorilla, like the skunk, can "shoot" its fragrant secret at considerable distances.

Although the smell of their secretions is not as "fragrant" and pungent as that of the American striped skunk, but, nevertheless, it is unpleasant and durable. When a strong enemy attacks Zorilla, she can pretend to be dead if there is nowhere to run.

Zorillas are distributed south of the Sahara: from Senegal and Nigeria to South Africa. Body length 28-38 cm, tail 20-30 cm. The weight of females is 600-900 g, males 700-1500 g.

This carnivorous animal feeds mainly on mouse-like rodents, hares, large insects, sometimes bird eggs, snakes and other animals. In a hungry time, carrion can also be consumed. Leads a nocturnal lifestyle

text: The red howler

is distributed from Colombia to the Amazon and from Ecuador to central Bolivia.

These unhurried animals slowly climb trees, covering a distance of about 400 m per day. They are active mainly in the morning and afternoon hours. At night they sleep in trees.

The body length of the male is 50-70 cm, females 45-55 cm. Males weigh 6.5-8 kg, females from 4.5 to 6.4 kg.

Red howlers, like most other monkeys, have developed social behavior. Animals are grouped into groups numbering from five to twenty individuals. The group is headed by an old male. Other mature males also claim to be the leader of the group, so there are often clashes between them for primacy.

The diet includes peanuts, tree foliage, various seeds, fruits and flowers

text: The grizon (huron)

is a predator from the marten family, living from eastern Mexico to Bolivia, Argentina and Santa Catarina in Brazil.

The body length of the grison is 45-55 cm, the tail is 13-19 cm, the weight is 1.5-3.8 kg. The body is slender, with short legs. The color of the back is smoky gray, part of the muzzle below the forehead, the lower part of the neck and belly are painted black. A white stripe on the forehead runs along the sides of the neck to the shoulders.

In case of danger, the grison makes a warning sound and jumps to the side, raising its tail and spraying a fragrant secret from the anal glands.

The grison feeds on small mammals, birds and their eggs, lizards, amphibians and fruits. It hunts both alone and in pairs or groups. He eats his prey in a specially designated place.

The grison keeps mainly on the ground, less often on trees or bushes. Animals swim well, sometimes dive, holding their breath for half a minute.

text: The red-faced (black) coata

is a spider monkey living in the rainforests of northern South America. The species suffers from hunting and destruction of their habitats by humans, so the IUCN classifies it as vulnerable.

Red-faced cats have long black fur and a red or pink face, naked except for a few short, white hairs. Cubs are born with dark faces, blushing as they grow up.

The average body length is 55 cm, and the weight is about 9 kg. The tail is prehensile (capable of grasping), the fingers and limbs are long, mobile and strong.

Red-faced cats are omnivorous. They eat termites and larvae, as well as soft leaves, flowers, berries and fruits.

¬†The life span in captivity is up to 33 years

text: Arasari

among all toucans are distinguished by the brightest plumage.

They are found in upland areas from southern Mexico to Argentina. These birds live in groups and inhabit dense relict forests.

Their food consists mainly of fruits, insects, bird eggs and lizards. As a nest and shelter, they use tree hollows, from which they sometimes expel the woodpeckers nesting there.

These are relatively small toucans with a body length of up to 45 cm and a weight of no more than 250 g. The large beak does not cause inconvenience to the arasari: it is very light due to the presence of pneumatic cavities in it. The notches on the beak help them to hold and open the fruits.

Because of their huge beak, arasari fly quite hard. After taking off, the bird gains altitude, and then plans in the right direction, describing wide circles in the air. Long-distance flights are avoided.

text: The crested auklet

belongs to the purebred, lives in the North Pacific Ocean and the Bering Sea.

This bird species feeds on krill and various small marine animals, diving into deep waters. It breeds in dense colonies of up to 1 million individuals in the Bering and Okhotsk Seas.

Auklets are known for their characteristics, which are found in both males and females. These include colorful plumage with a crest on the forehead, a striking citrus-like fragrance, and a loud trumpet call - all of which apparently evolved as a result of sexual selection.

The crests on the forehead vary greatly and can have from two to twenty-three narrow feathers. The average horse has 12 tufted feathers of different lengths from 8 to 60 mm.

A large auklet can reach 18-27 cm in length, 35-50 cm in wingspan and weigh 200-330 g.

The social smell that the auklets emit during the breeding season is described as the smell of tangerines. It is felt by people at a distance of about 1 km from the colony!

messages.text:
The Anhinga got its name due to its long thin neck, which looks like a snake when swimming, when the rest of the body is hidden under water.

It is a fairly large bird with a body length of 85 cm, a wingspan of 115 cm and a weight of up to 1.35 kg.

The word "anhinga" comes from the Brazilian Tupi language and means "devil bird" or "snake-like bird".

How does this bird manage to swim, completely immersed in the water? Very simple: unlike ducks, the snake snake cannot make its feathers waterproof using oil produced by the coccygeal gland, so its feathers can get completely wet, which makes the bird barely buoyant. However, this allows it to easily dive and search for underwater prey such as fish and amphibians.

After several dives, the anhinga has to dry its wings for a long time, in this it is similar to a cormorant. It is curious that anhinga necks do not have external nostrils, and they breathe exclusively with the epiglottis

text:
Marmoset and a terrible grasshopper.

The diet of dwarf marmosets

consists mainly of gum and tree sap, but sometimes they also eat fruits, flowers, nectar and insects. This marmoset has encountered a grasshopper and is completely confused, mistaking it for a reality-defying "walking leaf".

Igrunki live in South America near the shores of the Atlantic Ocean. The body length of adult monkeys is 20-25 cm, and the weight is up to 300 g.

Life expectancy is 15-18 years. The needs of a marmoset cannot be compared with the needs of an ordinary hamster, which can be locked in a cage, leaving toys and food. If we can leave the pets we are used to to ourselves, then this will not work with the igrunki. They do not just require high‚Äìquality care - monkeys need constant communication.  So think a hundred times before you decide to get this monkey!

text: Introducing the bird of paradise

, recognized as a new species due to its smooth dance movements.

In 2016, researchers at the Cornell Laboratory of Ornithology participated in a multimedia expedition as part of the Birds of Paradise project in the far western region of New Guinea, called the Bird's Head Peninsula (Vogelkop), when they happened to hear a characteristic song.

Ornithologists knew that the population of the Magnificent Bird of Paradise found there sings a different song than individuals elsewhere in New Guinea, so they set up their equipment to record the mating dance - and found that this bird was sliding from side to side, not jumping, and its feathers were fluttering in a crescent fan, not oval.

These and other differences were enough to suggest that scientists had discovered a new species! Which was supported by DNA analysis

text: The white-headed (pale) saki

reaches a length of 30 to 50 cm, the fluffy tail is the same length as the body and does not look like a monkey at all! Besides, he's not grasping.

The weight ranges from about 1.5 to 1.8 kg, and males are slightly heavier. The hind legs are much longer than the front ones. The coat is long and shaggy.

The pale saki inhabits northeastern South America. Its range covers eastern Venezuela, Guyana, Suriname, French Guiana and northeastern Brazil north of the Amazon. Its living space is forests, and they can be found both in the depths of the jungle and in mountain forests.

The diet of these animals consists mainly of seeds and fruits, in a small amount they consume other parts of plants and insects

text: The Himalayan monal

belongs to the pheasant, this bird is the national symbol of Nepal.
The females are painted in low-key brown tones, the male shimmers with all the colors of the rainbow, his plumage is shiny, and his head is decorated with a green crest of rather long feathers with white tips.
These birds are inhabitants of the highlands of Central Asia. They deftly run and walk on mountains, their legs are strong, and their wings are wide and short.
Monals fly well, but reluctantly, like many other chickens. The monal's beak is powerful, somewhat curved downwards, it is mostly a herbivorous bird, feeding on seeds and green parts of plants, but they do not miss insects, of course.
From the shrubby thickets where the Mongols hide during the day, they go out to feed on more open slopes - most often in the mornings and evenings. In summer, they go up to the mountains to feed, to the level of eternal snows. Usually you can see small groups of birds consisting of a male and several females

text:
belongs to pheasants, and lives in the Himalayas in India, Tibet, Bhutan, Nepal and Southern China.

The whole genus of tragopans (or horned pheasants) is named after the goat-legged ancient god Pan for "horns" and "beard". And the specific name "satyr" is also associated with ancient mythology and is due to the same "horns".

Prefers moist mountain oak and mixed forests with dense undergrowth of rhododendrons and bamboo. It is also found along the banks of rivers and streams overgrown with dense shrubs and various grasses.

During the year, the tragopan-satyr makes vertical migrations within the boundaries of its range, descending lower in winter and climbing higher into the mountains in summer. In nature, birds lead a secretive lifestyle, males are especially careful.

One of the reasons for the decline in the number of satyrs remains poaching, as well as tourism. However, this pheasant lives well and reproduces in captivity, and it is successfully kept in many zoos and nurseries

text: The tenacious-tailed porcupine

is distributed in tropical forests from Colombia and Venezuela in the south to northern Argentina.

The way of life is arboreal, it rarely descends to the ground, for watering. He walks lightly on the ground, but slowly. Active at night. During the day he sleeps at a height of 6-10 m . Prehensile-tailed porcupines live in small groups. Their easily falling needles serve as an effective means of protection from predators.

The captured animal is rolled into a ball. It feeds on leaves, buds, and fruits. Sometimes it ruins plantations of guava, corn and bananas.

It is a small animal with a body length of up to 65 cm and a weight of up to 5 kg. The needles are short, thick, tricolor: pale yellow above and below, and black in the center. The color of the back is black, the belly is gray. The tail is prehensile, usually devoid of needles, 30-50 cm long

messages.text:
The Brazilian saved the penguin - and now he sails every year!

Brazilian pensioner Joao Pereira de Souza has an unusual loyal friend: a wild penguin comes to visit him every year again and again, because grandfather saved the bird from imminent death.

In 2011, a resident of a fishing village found a baby penguin on the rocks near Rio de Janeiro, stained with oil. The bird could not move and feed on its own. Grandpa took the baby penguin home, washed it and fed it. Gave him the nickname Dindim.¬†

A few months later, when the penguin had adult plumage, he left his savior and, joining his relatives, went to the coast of Argentine Patagonia. From Rio it is 8000km.

De Souza had already said goodbye to his friend forever, but the next year the penguin returned, as if nothing had happened, and again lived with his grandfather for several months. And sailed back to Argentina. And this has been happening for four years in a row.

Dindim considers de Souza a member of his family and thinks that he is also a penguin!

messages.text:
The stork and the doomed chick.

Nature is not cruel, nature is expedient. Feeling that she cannot feed three chicks, the stork mother chooses the weakest one and throws it out of the nest so that the remaining ones get more food.

Most likely, the unlucky chick will die - but there is a chance that a person will pick it up and feed it. And then those of you who are now scolding the stork will weep over the poor stork living with people: ‚Äî Aaaah, the bird must live in the wild! Because you will never please everyone

text: The Danaida monarch

is one of the most famous butterflies of North America.

In the XIX century, representatives of this species were found in New Zealand and Australia. In Europe, they are common in the Canary Islands and Madeira.

Monarch butterflies are notable for their annual migrations to the south from southern Canada and the northern states of the USA to Florida, California and Mexico from August to the first frosts, traveling 3-4 thousand km or more on the way. After wintering in the mountains of Mexico, these butterflies go on a journey back to the north.

And this is the Mariposa Monarch Biosphere Reserve (monarch Butterfly Reserve), which is located in the Mexican state of Michoacan and a hummingbird robot to observe them

text: The spiny mountain turtle

lives in Southeast Asia (in Manyama, Thailand, the Malacca Peninsula, Borneo and nearby Indonesian islands).

It usually inhabits woodlands near mountain streams. This young spiny mountain turtle still has sharp spikes along the edge of the shell, however, as it grows, these notches wear out and smooth out, and the turtle acquires a more rounded shape. They can grow up to 23 cm .

Young turtles lead a more land-based lifestyle than adults. But both adults and young stay in moist rain forests.

These turtles feed mainly on plant foods, in particular greens, fruits, berries. They also hunt small invertebrates.

Unfortunately, these beautiful and exotic animals belong to an endangered species...

text: Geoffroy's cat

lives in South America. Its range extends from Bolivia and southern Brazil to Patagonia. It is found exclusively east of the Andes.

Body length 45-75 cm, tail 25-35 cm. The weight of the animal is from 4 to 5 kg, but sometimes there are larger representatives of this species.

The cat's coat is short and very soft, the color is golden yellow with black spots all over the body. In the northern areas of its habitat, the Geoffroy cat is painted in juicy ochre, whereas in the south of its range, the Geoffroy cat is silver-gray.

The eyes are quite large, set low, the paws are equipped with strong retractable claws, with which the cat climbs trees. In addition, the animal firmly holds the caught prey with its claws. She has perfectly developed hearing and vision. Can swim.

Geoffroy's cat prey includes birds, insects, reptiles, hares and rodents. Since it often hunts fish in the water, it is also called a "fishing cat".

text: The crowned crane

performs a mating dance.

This amazing bird leads a sedentary lifestyle in West and East Africa. There is a small red throat sac under the chin, similar to that of a rooster or turkey, but it is able to inflate.

The legs are black. Unlike many other cranes, the crowned crane has a long rear toe on its leg, which allows the bird to easily hold on to a branch of a tree or shrub.

It lives in savannas south of the Sahara, as well as in eastern Africa in Uganda, Rwanda, Burundi, Sudan and Ethiopia. It lives in open spaces - both swampy and more arid, but prefers swamps with fresh water, flood meadows or the shores of reservoirs.

This crane can also be found in the fields of rice or other moisture-loving crops. Often in habitats you can see acacias or other trees on which birds settle down for the night. The crowned crane is not afraid of humans and often settles near human habitation

text: Palm black cockatoos

are one of the few bird species that use instruments to create sound.

Since females are very picky about their nests, males build them only in the hollows of certain trees, and then use sticks and drum with them to lure females to inspect the nests.

This is a very large parrot with a body length of 70-80 cm . It lives in northern Australia, Cape York Peninsula, New Guinea and nearby islands. This species is the oldest cockatoo species in Australia. He was the first to settle the northern part of this continent.

These parrots live extremely long - up to 90 years. Black cockatoos have more than enough time to learn the most difficult things

text: The brilliant gulman

lives in the rain forests of Indonesia - the island of Java and nearby small islands.
Like other langurs, these monkeys have a long tail up to a meter in length, while their body length is about 55 cm.
They are active during the day, spend most of their time in trees. The diet is mainly vegetable: they eat leaves, fruits, flowers, buds. Sometimes insect larvae are included in the diet. The digestive system is adapted for the digestion of coarse vegetable food.
But scientists are silent about one thing! It is enough to look at these gloomy serious faces and it becomes clear: these are misanthropic philosophers...

text: The long-legged

belongs to the marsupial kangaroo rats, these milahs live in Eastern Australia and on the island of Tasmania.¬†

According to them, they lead a terrestrial lifestyle. Activity occurs at night, although sometimes they bask in the sun in the early morning. The day is spent in shallow burrows, usually dug at the base of grass hummocks. Complex burrows are not built.

They feed on the aboveground parts of herbaceous plants and roots. A significant proportion of the daily diet in the period from May to June consists of mushrooms (more than 70%), as well as insects (primarily in summer).

Potoru sniffs the ground, moving from side to side - and as soon as he finds a possible source of food (with the help of his sense of smell), he begins digging with his front paws

text: The African black-bellied pangolin

feeds almost exclusively on ants, and it is the only known species of pangolin whose diet does not depend on termites.

Also called long-tailed pangolins, they live in the forests of west and central Africa. This pangolin found a nest of tree ants.

It is curious that the name "pangolin" comes from the Malay pengguling - "curling into a ball", because pangolins live not only in Africa, but also in Asia - China, Java, Malaysia.
Anthills serve pangolins not only as a dining room, but also as a kind of "cleaning station" from parasites. At the same time, the beast sits down near a cluster of angry ants and spreads its scales. Insects climb under them and begin to bite pangolin painfully, watering his skin with formic acid, but he tolerates it.
Then the pangolin quickly presses the scales to the body and crushes the ants, which is where the cleansing procedure ends.¬†
However, this walking pine cone loves to splash in the water, just like any other animal!

text: The giant marsupial marten

is the second largest marsupial predator after the Tasmanian devil and the largest marsupial predator of mainland Australia.

Its body length is about 60-75 cm, tail 50 cm, weight up to 7 kg. The color of the fur is dark brown, differs from other species by the presence of white spots on the tail (and not only on the body). These martens arrange a den in an underground burrow, cave, hollow tree, hollow log, rock crevices and even under people's houses.

The usual habitats are moist rain forests and coastal thickets along the coast. These are nocturnal animals leading a solitary lifestyle.

Their diet consists mainly of rabbits and other small mammals (2/3 of their diet), birds, bird eggs and reptiles. However, due to its size and strength, the gigantic marsupial marten also hunts larger animals: herons, tree possums and even young wallaby kangaroos.

text: The

whalehead is a large water bird that can be unmistakably recognized by its unique "shoe-shaped" beak, reminding that birds descended from dinosaurs.

These monsters live in Africa, the Arabs call this bird Abu markub, which means "slipper".

These are tall birds - from 110 to 140 cm . The length from tail to beak can range from 100 to 140 cm, wingspan from 230 to 260 cm, and weight from 4 to 7 kg.

Given the huge beak with sharp edges and a wide entrance hole, the whalehead can hunt larger prey than other wading birds.

The main tactics used by the whale heads are "stand and wait", as well as "wander slowly". When prey is found, the bird's head quickly sinks into the water, as a result of which it often loses its balance and falls. After that, the whaler must regain his balance and start again from a standing position.

I must say that the whale-head is not very clever and often hunts for any garbage - as in this video, where he grabs a stick instead of a yummy

text: Gulman (langur, hanuman)

is revered in India as a sacred animal, the personification of the god Hanuman.

This monkey is also common in Nepal, Southern Tibet, Sri Lanka, Bangladesh.

They climb trees and their crowns well, are capable of jumping 4-12 meters long and jumping from a great height, although they spend most of their time on the ground during the day, running well on all fours, and always spend the night in trees. They are active mainly in the morning and evening hours.

They feed mainly on fruits, flowers, tree bark, buds of trees and shrubs, grass and leaves, less often small insects and bird eggs, but often harm agricultural plantations, sometimes even making real raids on them.

Because of their sacred status in Hinduism, killing or any action against this monkey, even shouting at it, is considered a sin, which is why many raids on plantations and even people's homes, from where these monkeys can carry things and food, remain mostly unpunished.

text: The scaly gecko

is a genus of geckos, also called fish geckos for their large scales.

These nocturnal arboreal insectivorous lizards are endemic to Madagascar and the Comoros.

They are best known for their ability to lose skin and scales when captured by a predator.

Their specific name "megalepis" means "very large scales" in Greek. The discarded skin along with the scales is restored after a few weeks without forming scars

text: The Nakunda (white-bellied nightjar)

, which lives in South America, never leaves its native places. In the most difficult months, when it is especially difficult to get food, it goes into hibernation. 10 grams of stored fat is enough for a bird to hibernate for up to 100 days.

This species of nightjars is notable for its partially diurnal lifestyle. Despite the fact that the nighthawk (as it is mistakenly called in Argentina) hunts in the air, it spends a significant amount of time on the ground; it has particularly long legs for the nightjar, and it can be seen walking on the ground more often than other species, rather than resting on its surface.

Previously, nakunda belonged to the monotypic genus Podager, but in 2011 it was reclassified into the mouth of Chordeiles. The former generic name podager came from the Latin "a man suffering from gout" and reflects the clumsy manner of walking of this nighthawk.

The species name nacunda comes from a Guarani Indian word meaning "big mouth"

messages.text:
While toothed whales have only one nostril (blowhole), baleen whales have two nostrils, and they have a much better sense of smell than toothed whales.

During the evolution of whales, their nostrils migrated up and back to the top of the head, allowing them to function as blowholes. Toothed whales have fewer functional olfactory receptor genes compared to baleen whales, and they have lost a number of brain and nerve structures associated with olfaction.

It has been suggested that the loss of sense of smell in toothed whales may be related to the specialization of the skull and soft tissues for echolocation. However, it has also been hypothesized that filter-feeding whales retained their sense of smell to detect shoals of plankton

text: Guajaro

- aka fat nightjar.
And what to call it, if the other nightjars weigh at most 150-200 g, and this one - 500 g?! And the generic name Steatornis means "fat bird".

Other indicators are not inferior: it is a bird the size of a chicken, its length from beak to tail is about 45 cm, and its wingspan is up to 90 cm.

This nightjar lives in the northern part of South America, where it nests in large caves located in inaccessible moist forests.

Guajaros are colonial birds. They inhabit caves, navigating in the dark with the help of echolocation (!).

They feed at night, mainly on the fruits of palm trees containing a large amount of oil, as well as the fruits of trees of the laurel family. In search of food, the birds fly out of the caves around 6 p.m. and return back around 6 a.m. In total, they can fly a distance of about 100-150 km per night!

text: The mountain (southern) viscacha

is a rodent of the chinchilla family found in Argentina, Bolivia, Chile and Peru

They live in mountainous areas with sparse vegetation at altitudes of 2400-5000 m . In their appearance, they resemble rabbits with a long tail, like squirrels.

The length of the body of mountain whiskers reaches 40 cm, and the tail up to 32 cm, weight according to various sources from 1.5 to 3 kg.

Viskashi lead a daytime lifestyle, they are most active near sunrise and sunset. They feed on grass, mosses and lichens - at the same time they do not need water, since they have enough of the water that is contained in plants.

People hunt viscach because of their fur and meat. Due to hunting, the number of whiskash is decreasing.

In the wild, mountain whiskies live only 3 years, and in captivity, with proper care, they live up to 19 years

text:
Don't faint! These spiders are completely harmless. They are not poisonous and cannot bite through human skin.

Frin (flagellated spider)

is the oldest inhabitant of our planet, as evidenced by the fossil remains of animals that have lain in the ground for more than 358 million years.

Phryns are heat-loving and moisture-loving animals, so they live in Africa, Australia, India, China, Vietnam, Thailand, Singapore, Haiti, Malaysia, Indonesia and many other countries with a tropical climate.

The body of the phryne, in comparison with other arachnids, is not so large: from 5 mm to 4.5-5 cm and has a flattened shape. And the uncanny appearance of the animal is given disproportionately long legs, exceeding the length of the trunk by 5 times and growing up to 25 cm or more. 

The main difference between phryns and spiders is the absence of spider and venom glands. For all their intimidating appearance, phryns are absolutely harmless and pose a danger only to small insects that they eat

messages.text:
Sand Bubbler Crabs  live on sandy beaches in the tropical Indo-Pacific region. This video was shot in Australia.

These are small crabs, only 1-1.5 cm across the shell. They eat a thin layer of edible particles on the grains of sand. The grains of sand are scraped off with downward-pointing claws and brought to the mouthpiece, which filters out these tiny particles.

The displaced sand is then rolled into a small ball and ejected. As the sand is processed, a path is scraped from the entrance to the burrow, and small balls of sifted sand are piled on both sides of this path.

Sand bubble crabs are responsible for the delicate patterns of tiny balls on sandy shores at low tide. Crabs appear as soon as the water recedes. You can find out when the tide was high by drawing sand balls. The more complex the drawing, the more time has passed since the tide.

And the Sand Bubbler Crabs wait out the tide in their burrows, which are covered from above with the same sand

text: The flamebird

is one of the most brightly colored representatives of the arbor family of birds living only in the tropical forests of New Guinea.

Males of these birds, like other types of shelters, build a "gazebo" from twigs and grass to attract the attention of females. Near the "gazebo" there is a courtship process, during which he takes a "gift" in his beak and presents it to his chosen one.

Just look at this dance! And at his humble only spectator. And for this present...

text_entities.text: The flamebird
Ptilonorhynchus violaceus

is one of the most brightly colored representatives of the arbor family of birds living only in the tropical forests of New Guinea.

Males of these birds, like other types of shelters, build a "gazebo" from twigs and grass to attract the attention of females. Near the "gazebo" there is a courtship process, during which he takes a "gift" in his beak and presents it to his chosen one.

Just look at this dance! And at his humble only spectator. And for this present...

text: The Malayan woolwing

lives in Thailand, the Malay Peninsula, Sumatra, Java and Borneo.

The body length of the Malay woolwing is 30-40 cm, the tail is 15-20 cm. The span of the limbs is 70-120 cm, and the weight is 1-1.75 kg.

It prefers moist jungles in hilly areas, but is also found on coconut and banana plantations. They are herbivores that feed on flowers, leaves, buds and fruits.

This kind of animal lives in trees and never voluntarily descends to the ground. These are solitary animals, occasionally you can meet several individuals on the same tree.

They use a gliding flight to move from one tree to another without touching the ground. More often they fly at a distance of up to 50-70 m, the record flight range was 136 m.

The animals are active at night, spending the day in their shelter. The gestation period lasts 60 days, then a cub (at least two) weighing only 35 g is born. When the female jumps, the cub hides in the folds of her mother's skin, forming a kind of bag

messages.text:
The Amur forest cat belongs to Bengal cats and is related to the Amur tiger and the Far Eastern leopard.

In many literary sources, it is found under the name of the Far Eastern cat. People for a long time did not attach importance to this type of animal, as a result of which their population has significantly decreased and these cats are almost on the verge of extinction.

Many zoologists believe that Amur tigers and forest cats have common ancient ancestors and their history goes back about one and a half million years.

Among the representatives of the feline family, Amur cats are one of the smallest. The weight of one adult is 6-8 kg. The height at the withers is 40-50 cm, the body length is about a meter.

Sexual dimorphism is expressed in these animals ‚Äì females are more fragile and graceful compared to males. Amur cats have a long thin and very fluffy tail, reaching 40 cm in length.

A distinctive feature of the animals is the presence of a strip of bare skin on the bridge of the nose

text: Argus monitor lizard

lives on sandy expanses and along the banks of rivers in Australia and New Guinea.¬†Going out to hunt and bask in the sun from its deep burrow, the Argus monitor lizard, like a snake, catches odors in the air with its long forked tongue.
‚†Ä
And if he feels danger nearby, he takes such a threatening pose: he stands on his hind legs and inflates his neck!
‚†Ä
If there is no threat, the monitor lizard hunts any small animals it meets on its way: small mammals, insects, snakes, lizards and frogs, dives into the water for fish and crabs and climbs trees for birds.

Argus monitor lizard is quite an intelligent lizard, he is curious and often stands on his hind legs and in order to explore the territory around. Unlike many reptiles, the argus monitor lizard is described as a social species, forming pairs for life

text: Fox kuzu (fox-shaped possum)

lives in Australia and on the islands of New Zealand and Tasmania. It is also called brushtail or simply kuzu-fox. Its body length is 32-58 cm (females are smaller), tail 24-40 cm, weight from 1.2 to 4.5 kg.

Kuzu has a sharp muzzle and long ears, gray or brown fur, and albinos are also found. The tail is long and fluffy.

The fox kuzu lives in trees, is active at night. During the day it rests in hollows or in peculiar nests. Also suits the lairs. It feeds on leaves, berries, fruits.

Despite the fact that these marsupials are perfectly able to climb trees and are perfectly adapted for this type of movement, they are quite slow and lazy creatures.

The main predators that prey on fox cousins are birds of prey and monitor lizards. Previously, people destroyed these animals in significant volumes because of their valuable fur. It was exported from Australia under the name "Australian possum" or "Adelaide chinchilla". Today kuzu is under guard

text:
There are many amazing, even frightening creatures in the world. The latter include the star-bearing mole, which, if it does not lead, is necessarily included in the list of the most "ugly" animals of our planet. 

The star‚Äìbearing

is not an ordinary mole. He not only likes to walk on the surface of the earth, but also loves to swim in the water. And hard wool helps him in this, which has a water-repellent effect.

The star-shaped growth on the muzzle of this animal is unique. Scientists have found out that it can be called the most sensitive touch system in the world. More than one hundred thousand nerve endings are located on this organ. This indicator is five times more than the indicator of the sensitivity of the human hand!

In addition, the star-shaped nose is able to perceive odors even under water. To do this, the animal releases bubbles into the water, then draws them back. According to scientists, it is these bubbles that allow the mole to smell prey in the water

text:
When you are not in the upper echelons of the food chain and cannot rely on your brains and muscles to protect yourself from being eaten, you come up with other tricks. All kinds of protective mechanisms are involved in the animal world, and one of the most remarkable is mimicry.

Lichen grasshopper

is a great master of effective camouflage. The growth of lichen on the trees is the best shelter for this insect, which merges in color with the environment.

This grasshopper lives in South America in a thicket of lichens, it also feeds on them - and no one knows anything else about it ü§∑ 
Well, at least it was possible to notice and photograph it

text: The red-eyed tree frog

is a tree frog that lives in the rainforests of southern Mexico (Yucatan) and Central America.

These are nocturnal animals, during the day and during the drought season they hide on the underside of wide leaves, sleep on the tops of trees. During sleep, their bright red eyes are masked by the lower translucent eyelid, painted in a golden mesh, which allows the tree frog to see prey or danger.

With the onset of darkness, the tree frogs wake up, yawn, stretch, change their light green daytime color to dark green at night and announce the surroundings with a specific croak. They are capable of making very long jumps.

During rest, the eyes of the red-eyed tree frog are closed with a transparent membrane that does not prevent this frog from seeing the world around it. But if she is in danger, the tree frog immediately opens her eyes wide and confuses the predator with their bright red color - and these seconds are enough for her to instantly disappear!

messages.text:
This cameraman spent 76 days in the snow of the Yukon, filming the Canadian lynx and its hunt for hares. Gradually accustoming the animal to himself and his equipment, he managed to gain his trust and friendly relations developed between them.

The Canadian lynx is smaller than an ordinary one: body length is 85-115 cm, height at the withers is 60-65 cm, and weight is 8-14 kg.

The basis of its diet is just a white hare (up to 75%), the rest are birds, small rodents (squirrels, beavers, muskrats) and ungulates (red deer, snow sheep). In those years when the population of the white hare is declining, these lynxes practically do not reproduce - that is, their number is regulated by the amount of food available.

This cat lives in wooded areas of Alaska, Canada, as well as the states of Montana, Idaho, Washington and Colorado

messages.text:
Serengeti (Tanzania). The lioness protects the cubs from a pack of hyena dogs and reprimands the lazy husband: ‚Äî And where are you looking?! And Tom has to belatedly growl at the whole savannah...

The father of a small family was sleeping in a thicket of bushes. He snored so hard that the sound attracted wild African dogs. But they did not dare to wake up the king of the jungle, especially when they noticed a simpler prey: three small lion cubs. The lioness left them in the care of her negligent "spouse" when she went hunting.

The dogs, with their ears bent, headed towards the cubs, but then a lioness came out from behind the bushes, showing the dogs with all her formidable appearance that they were not welcome here.

After a short "tag game", the dogs left the territory of the lion family. Only then did the mother calm down and began to call the cubs with a soft and low growl. One by one they came to Mom, alive and well. But the male was waiting for a "serious conversation" on the topic of responsibility..

text: The bare-throated bell ringer

lives in the mountain rainforests in eastern Brazil, Paraguay and northern Argentina.

Most of the time, the bare-throated bell ringer stays in the upper part of the tree crowns. It feeds on fruits.

The male screams, sitting on a high branch and throwing his head back, thereby attracting the attention of the female. When a partner appears, he starts jumping from branch to branch with his tail feathers spread wide.

The metallic ringing voice is similar to the sound of a bell. This is the loudest of the sounds in the world of birds

text: The Indian star turtle

belongs to the land species, its length is 25 cm for females and 15 cm for males.

It has a very beautiful convex shell, which is why it is very popular with terrariumists. The star-shaped turtle got its name due to a peculiar pattern in the form of a yellow multipath star on each shield of the shell (except for the marginal ones).

This color, which seems bright and catchy in captivity, perfectly camouflages the turtle in nature when it hides between the curtains of dry grass. Males, in addition to size, differ from females also by less convex carapace shields.

The range of the star turtle covers India, southeastern Pakistan, Sri Lanka and nearby islands

messages.text:
Valonia ventricosa is one of the largest single-celled organisms!

It is known by the names "bubble algae", "cursed grape" and "sailor's eyeball". It is found all over the world in tropical and subtropical areas.

Valonia potbellied, as a rule, grows singly and only occasionally - in groups that appear in tidal zones of tropical and subtropical zones - such as the Caribbean Islands, north to Florida, south to Brazil and in the Indo-Pacific region. It often lives in coral deposits. It occurs at depths up to 80 m .

It is a single-celled multicellular organism, which can vary in shape from spherical to oval, color from herbaceous green to dark green. In the water, it may turn out to be silver, sea-green and even blackish.

The intensity of the color is determined by the number of chloroplasts in the cell. The surface of the algae is mirror-shiny, like glass, and the diameter ranges from 1 to 4 cm, but can sometimes reach 5 cm.
